The push and pull workflow.

The full cycle for getting an image you built onto a registry has four steps. First you tag your local image with the registry-qualified name, and you can give it several tags at once, like a version and latest. Then you authenticate to the registry with docker login. Then you push the tags. And finally, on another machine, you pull the image by its qualified name and run it. That is the whole loop, and it is the same for every registry.

The interesting part is what actually gets uploaded. When you push, the daemon walks the image's layers in order, and for each one it computes the digest, which it already has from the build, and asks the registry whether it already has that digest. If the answer is yes, it skips the layer and uploads no bytes. If the answer is no, it streams the layer up. So pushing a new build that shares ninety percent of its layers with the previous build uploads only the ten percent that changed, because the shared base layers were already there. This content-addressable deduplication is why a push can be dramatically faster than the image's size would suggest.

It is also worth being precise about what tagging does. Tagging does not copy any data. It just adds another name pointing at the same image, the same manifest digest. So after tagging one built image with several names, they all refer to the identical bytes on disk, with the identical digest. That is why tagging is free, and why teams routinely tag one image with a version, a commit hash, and latest before pushing, paying just a single upload for all of them.
